04525nam a22005535i 9780773555693DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735556937 a10.1515/97807735556932doi  a(DE-B1597)657092  a(OCoLC)1059577200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9198.3.M62bC65 2018eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a813/.540932714272231 aColeman, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEquivocal City :bFrench and English Novels of Postwar Montreal /cPatrick Coleman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Texts and Translations -- tIntroduction -- tSolitude and the City in the 1940s -- tPolitics and Promiscuity in Hugh MacLennan’s Two Solitudes -- tGendered Mediations -- tTemptation and Tenderness in Gabrielle Roy’s Bonheur d’occasion (The Tin Flute) -- tShaky Solidarities: The 1950s -- tWitnesses to Weakness -- tA Precarious Maturity -- tFailing Better -- tSolutions and Dissolutions -- tTwilight of the Idols, Dawn of a New Day -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of Montreal as a specific location in French and English writings has long been subordinated to the demands of linguistically divided and politically contentious narratives about national development. In this cross-linguistic study, Patrick Coleman models an inclusive and post-national literary history of the city itself. Tracing a sequence of moments in the emergence of the Montreal novel from World War II to the turbulent 1960s, Equivocal City offers close readings of fourteen key works of fiction, focusing on the inner dynamic of their construction as well as the unexpected convergences and contrasts in the narrative structures they adopt and the aesthetic perspective they seek to achieve. Critically sophisticated but accessibly written, this book gives a sympathetic account of how writers in both languages struggled to give integrated artistic expression to their experience of a city that was still linguistically compartmentalized and culturally insecure. By analyzing the interplay between story and narrative form, the book explores what French and English novelists could – and could not – imagine about the Montreal they sought to portray. From the responsible realism of Hugh MacLennan and Gabrielle Roy to the fractious phantasmagorias of Jacques Ferron and Leonard Cohen, Equivocal City traces the evolution of the Montreal novel with the aim of retrieving a shareable literary past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian fictionzQuébec (Province)zMontréaly20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian fictionzQuébec (Province)zMontréaly20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian fictionzQuébec (Province)zMontréaly20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian fictionzQuébec (Province)zMontréaly20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773555693?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555693/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles